### 1. One-Line Summary
Rakza 7 is the more classic, grippy, balanced all-round offensive rubber with a slightly more forgiving and stable personality, while Etika Pro 47 is the more modern, firmer, more direct attacking option with higher pace and sharper finishing power.

### 2. Head-to-Head Breakdown
* **Speed & Gears:**
    * **Low Impact:** Rakza 7 is a bit easier in soft exchanges because the response is more settled and less abrupt. Etika Pro 47 feels slightly more compact and firmer, so short touch shots require a little cleaner hand control.
    * **Top End:** Etika Pro 47 has the higher ceiling when you accelerate hard. It comes through the ball with more penetrating pace, whereas Rakza 7 tops out a little earlier.
    * **Linearity:** Rakza 7 is the more linear rubber overall. Its speed build-up is easier to read. Etika Pro 47 is still controlled, but it has a more offensive “extra gear” when you engage the sponge more fully.

* **Spin Mechanics:**
    * **Opening Loop:** Rakza 7 is usually easier for opening against backspin because the topsheet grip and throw profile help lift the ball with confidence. Etika Pro 47 can also open well, but it asks for slightly better timing and a more committed acceleration.
    * **Max Spin:** Etika Pro 47 can produce heavier spin at full commitment because of its stronger sponge response and higher-quality power transfer on harder loops. Rakza 7 is still very spinny, but its advantage is easier access rather than absolute peak.
    * **Topsheet Grip:** Rakza 7 feels more “grabby” in the classic sense. Etika Pro 47 is grippy too, but the overall feeling is more modern, compact, and speed-oriented rather than dwell-oriented.

* **Flight Path (Throw Angle):**
    * **Arc Height:** Rakza 7 tends to give the slightly safer and naturally higher arc. Etika Pro 47 is generally a bit flatter and more direct.
    * **Safety:** Rakza 7 offers more margin over the net for most players, especially in opening loops and controlled topspins. Etika Pro 47 rewards confident stroke commitment but gives a slightly smaller passive safety window.

* **Feel & Feedback:**
    * **Sensation:** Rakza 7 has a more classic, readable contact with clearer feedback for spin and placement. Etika Pro 47 feels firmer, denser, and more “performance tuned.”
    * **Dwell:** Rakza 7 gives a touch more dwell sensation. Etika Pro 47 releases the ball a bit faster, which helps direct offense but reduces the held-ball feeling slightly.

* **Control & Short Game:**
    * **Sensitivity:** Rakza 7 is a little calmer and easier in receives, pushes, and service touch. Etika Pro 47 is not wild, but the firmer directness means you need a more precise racket angle.
    * **Touch Play:** Rakza 7 is better for players who value easy length control and spin variation in the short game. Etika Pro 47 is better when you want to transition quickly from touch to attack.

* **Blocking & Countering:**
    * **Passive Block:** Rakza 7 is generally more forgiving on passive blocks because it absorbs pace a bit more naturally. Etika Pro 47 is stable, but it works best when you stay active.
    * **Active Counter:** Etika Pro 47 is stronger here. It bites and shoots forward better on punch blocks, counters, and power exchanges. Rakza 7 can counter well too, but it feels less explosive.

### 3. The Recommendation
* **Choose Rakza 7 if:**
    * You want the more balanced and versatile rubber.
    * You value easier opening loops, safer arc, and more intuitive short-game control.
    * You prefer a classic offensive feel with strong spin access and dependable linearity.
    * You are an all-round attacker, controlled looper, or developing offensive player who wants confidence over raw top-end power.

* **Choose Etika Pro 47 if:**
    * You want more direct speed and a higher finishing ceiling.
    * You play a more modern aggressive topspin game and like firmer contact.
    * You are comfortable generating your own acceleration and do not need as much built-in arc safety.
    * You prioritize active countering, direct pressure, and stronger power on full strokes.
